{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Log entries with the same trace ID are grouped together regardless of which microservice emitted them.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is module handoff: parsed records from different service sources must converge in the correlator and be keyed only by trace ID. A unit test of only the grouping function can miss wiring bugs where service-specific ingestion paths alter or drop the trace key before correlation.","test_description":"Run an in-process pipeline test wiring parser/ingest adapters to correlator. Feed mixed JSON records from multiple services sharing trace IDs and assert one group per trace ID across services.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The timeline view orders entries by timestamp, correctly handling clock skew of up to 500ms between services.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior depends on interaction between correlation context and ordering/skew-adjustment logic across service-originated events. No real OS/network/subprocess is required, and no AI output is involved.","test_description":"Wire correlator + timeline builder in-process. Provide cross-service events with controlled timestamp offsets (including +/-500ms edge cases) and assert final timeline order matches skew policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A latency spike (p99 above 3x the baseline) is detected and flagged in the anomaly report.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is often at the boundary between metrics aggregation (baseline/p99 computation) and reporting/flag emission. A pure unit on percentile math can miss incorrect propagation or threshold application in report generation.","test_description":"Execute in-process aggregation + anomaly-report modules over synthetic latency windows where p99 crosses and does not cross 3x baseline; assert correct flag presence in produced report.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.45,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Malformed JSON log entries are skipped without crashing the pipeline, and the count of skipped entries is reported.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure mode is parser error handling plus pipeline continuity plus counter/report propagation. Unit-testing JSON parse failure alone does not verify that the end-to-end in-process pipeline neither crashes nor misreports skipped count.","test_description":"Run parser + processing pipeline + reporting in-process with a mixed stream of valid and malformed JSON entries. Assert processing completes, malformed entries are skipped, and skipped-entry count matches expected.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The tool handles a burst of 10,000 log entries per second without dropping entries or falling behind.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a runtime throughput/backpressure behavior that depends on real scheduling, timing, buffering, and possibly OS I/O characteristics. In-process mocks/fakes can hide drops or lag that appear only under real load conditions.","test_description":"Run a system load test that drives the actual executable/process with a real high-rate input stream at 10,000 entries/sec, then verify ingest count equals sent count and processing lag stays within defined bound during and after burst.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
